2/11/19, 11:49 PM - Juan Barbosa: The extraction and quantification of food components, such as proteins, is of vital importance for the nutritional aspects of medicine and, in general, for biochemistry itself. In the present document two samples of common foods, wheat and egg, which have been in the diet of humans for a long time, were studied by means of UV-VIS spectroscopy. Wheat flour was one of the first foods discovered by human civilization and has been one of the main sources of polysaccharides, lipids and proteins since then. Furthermore, eggs have been, since ancient times, a very important food for man and its consumption is widespread worldwide currently. Depending on their function, proteins can be classified as structural, metabolic and storage proteins, like gluten, which is found commonly in wheat flour. Although the results show significant variance, protein content was quantified between 0.706 g and 0.284 g per 100 g of wheat, and 10 mg/mL and 110 mg/mL for egg.
2/11/19, 11:49 PM - Juan Barbosa: con tu nuevo parrafo,
2/11/19, 11:49 PM - Juan Barbosa: The extraction and quantification of food components, such as proteins, is of vital importance for the nutritional aspects of medicine and, in general, for biochemistry itself. In the present document two samples of common foods, wheat and egg, which have been in the diet of humans for a long time, were studied by means of UV-VIS spectroscopy. For this purpose, we carried out the corresponding sample preparation, solution and dilutions to make to make a calibration curve later. Wheat flour was one of the first foods discovered by human civilization and has been one of the main sources of polysaccharides, lipids and proteins since then. Furthermore, eggs have been, since ancient times, a very important food for man and its consumption is widespread worldwide currently. Depending on their function, proteins can be classified as structural, metabolic and storage proteins, like gluten, which is found commonly in wheat flour. Although the results show significant variance, protein content was quantified between 0.706 g and 0.284 g per 100 g of wheat, and 10 mg/mL and 110 mg/mL for egg.

3/25/19, 7:48 PM - MeÃ±eÃ±otes ğŸ˜½: Gram staining is a method used to differentiates bacteria by the chemical and physical properties of their cell walls by detecting peptidoglycan. Peptidoglycan is a polysaccharide present in the wall of gram-positive bacteria, while gram-negative bacteria do not have cellular wall. However, they have two membranes between which is found a small layer of peptidoglycan in small quantities. The process of staining consists of adding crystal violet to the sample which is retained by gram-positive bacteria, while gram-negative are not capable of retaining the dye because of the addition of ethanol which dehydrates the peptidoglycan layer, shrinking and tightening it, which in turn results in the discoloration of the staining. Gram-positive are not decolorized at all because of the natural thickness of its morphology. Additionally, the external membrane of gram-negative bacteria is composed primarily by lipopolysaccharides, which are directly affected by the addition of ethanol to the sample, leaving the peptidoglycan layer exposed to the external environment and making it easy to manipulate. Moreover, lugol  is an iodine solution that, in aqueous solution, dissociates and releases the iodine ion, which in turn forms a complex with the crystal violet dye added at the beginning and makes it possible to wash it out along with the outer membrane of the gram-negative cells. Finally, the latest addition of safranin is made up to dye the gram-negative bacteria that are, by this moment, translucent.

4/1/19, 11:06 PM - MeÃ±eÃ±otes ğŸ˜½: Por otro lado, es importante resaltar que el diseÃ±o de primers supone un punto crÃ­tico en la realizaciÃ³n de la PCR, puesto que de estos dependerÃ¡ la amplificaciÃ³n del fragmento de ADN de interÃ©s. Para esto es importante tener en cuenta que estas secuencias deben ser Ãºnicas, es decir, no deben ser complementarias a otras secuencias del fragmento de interÃ©s o permitir la uniÃ³n de las mismas a posibles contaminantes, puesto que esto asegura una alta especificidad y reproductibilidad de la amplificaciÃ³n. AdemÃ¡s, estos deben tener una longitud de entre 15-25 pares de bases, de manera que se pueda asegurar que la secuencia sea Ãºnica, pero no demasiado como para afectar la temperatura melting (Tm), es decir, la temperatura a la cual el 50% de los primers se encuentran anillados; y la cual a su vez depende de la fuerza iÃ³nica de la soluciÃ³n y del tamaÃ±o y composiciÃ³n del primer. Adicionalmente, esta secuencia no debe tener fragmentos complementarios entre si, puesto que esto favorece la formaciÃ³n de estructuras secundarias como hairpin Loops y dÃ­meros de primers.

Por otro lado, la proporciÃ³n Guanina-Citocina (G-C) de la secuencia tambien juega un papel fundamental en el diseÃ±o de primers, puesto que es importante que esta tenga una relaciÃ³n alta en comparaciÃ³n con la proporciÃ³n de Adenina-Timina. Lo anterior debido a que una proporciÃ³n de entre 45-50% de G-C asegura una buena temperatura de anillaje y estabilidad de hibridaciÃ³n , puesto que estas son pirimidinas que cuentan con un enlace triple. AdemÃ¡s, el porcentaje GC debe ser similar entre primers puesto que este afecta la especificidad de hibridaciÃ³n, la Tm y la temperatura de anillaje, de manera que si los primers difieren de Tm, en un rango mayor de 2-3ÂºC, no anillarÃ¡n a la misma temperatura, por lo que el proceso de amplificaciÃ³n se verÃ¡ aectado en mayor medida. Adicionalmente, es importante resaltar que la secuencia 3â€™ es crÃ­tica para el anillaje y amplificaciÃ³n de la secuencia, puesto que esta es la que cuenta con el extremo OH que hace posible el anclaje de la Polimerasa a la secuencia para la posterior amplificaciÃ³n, de forma que este extremo debe tener una alta proporciÃ³n G-C con el fin de garantizar el correcto anillaje en el sitio de amplificaciÃ³n.

5/30/19, 10:51 PM - MeÃ±eÃ±otes ğŸ˜½: Fermentation is a metabolic process of incomplete oxidation that takes place in the absence of oxygen. This is a catabolic process by which a great variety of microorganisms can obtain energy as ATP. This is the process carried out by Saccharomyces cerevisiae, which is the most widely used microorganism in the industry nowadays, for the manufacture of a number of products such as bread, beer and wine. In addition, fermentation is classified according to the final product of the metabolic pathway, so different types are known, such as alcoholic, butyric and acetic fermentation, among others. Between the last mentioned, alcoholic fermentation is the most studied because of its relevance in the industry, so during this experimental practice it was aimed to achieve the production of different alcoholic beverages from three different fermentable carbon sources, in order to evaluate the alcohol content and other physicochemical parameters, and thus determine the effect of the carbon source or initial substrate in the fermentation process. For this, the preparation of the different musts, the activation of the yeast, its inoculation and later determination of the production of carbon dioxide and quantification of ethanol were carried out.
